postcontent:
Ok, maybe it's not *your* ultimate AR but it's pretty close to mine. (unless I won the lotto).

So, I'm asking $5000 for all this stuff. I'm firm on that. If I need to add more goodies to get to where you feel that you are getting $5000 worth, I will, but I think I'm pretty close already.

What's included:

AR-15 based on DPMS lower and AAC 300 BLK upper. The upper is a 16" middy with Knights Armament Rail and AAC quick attach suppressor mount. Yes, I have a suppressor for this but I'm keeping it.

Mostly Magpul furniture including: Angled Foregrip, CTR stock, Winter trigger guard, B.A.D Lever and ladder rail covers.

Optic is a Horus Vision Talon. I went through a few scopes before I settled on this one. I really like this one a lot and I'm actually having a harder time parting with it than the rest of the gun.

AN-PVS14 Night Vision. Generation 3+ from US Nightvision. I bought this from Ready Made Resources. They hand select their NV for the clearest resolution, hence the 3+. The night vision is in excellent condition and comes with all the original accessories (not shown).

The PVS14 is mounted on a LaRue LT133 mount and I have it set up to be co-witnessed with the Horus. This is not the preferred setup, but it works. If I had $10k for the preferred setup, I'd think about it. : )

Troy Rear BUI and the Rail has a front sight integrated into it.

I have a LaRue Bipod mount. I don't use it much but it's nice for zeroing.

Travis Haley InForce Light with 45 degree mount. I really like this light. I went through a bunch of lights before I settled on this one.

SureFire M1 IR Light on LaRue 606 Mount. (Can you tell I like LaRue stuff?)

Redi-Mag.

Gear Sector Sling.

Not shown, but I'll throw in 10-30 round Pmags.

I also have a bunch of 300 BLK brass that you can have if you reload. About 1500 cases.

Don't email me if you're not serious. I'm not desperate to sell this and, as I said, the price is firm.

I'm not interested in trades except maybe a partial trade for a G17 or G19.

Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  Sig Sauer P238 .380 ACP Pistol with Rainbow Slide, Rosewood Grips, Night Sights, Black Frame – Sig Sauer 238-380-RBT
postcontent: We have hundreds of other guns currently IN STOCK, and offer some of Utah’s lowest prices! For a complete listing of our current inventory, and to purchase this and other guns online, please be sure to VISIT US ON THE WEB AT:  ***** TooeleShootingSupply.com *****  Not Your Average “Mouse” Gun. The Sig Sauer P238 is different from most other .380 “pocket” pistols on the market today. In terms of size and shape, the P238 is very similar to other comparable micro .380’s. Instead of a polymer frame, however, the Sig Sauer P238 uses an all metal frame with a single action design, and is almost identical in appearance to the legendary Colt Mustang.The Sig Sauer P238 operates with a locked-breech short recoil action. The hammer must be cocked either manually, or by the action of the slide, to fire each shot. The advantage to this method of operation is two- fold. First and foremost, similar to the Colt 1911 or Mustang, the Sig Sauer P238 has a superior trigger pull when compared to similarly sized double action only designs like the Ruger LCP, Smith & Wesson Bodyguard or Kel-Tec P3AT. In turn, this leads to greater accuracy. Second, the P238’s single action design allows Sig Sauer to incorporate a high ride beavertail grip frame, which leads to greater control under recoil by safely placing the shooter’s hand higher along the bore axis.In addition to being a great-looking pistol, the Sig Sauer P238 is much easier to load than other micro pistols on the market. For shooters that do not possess strong hands, the P238’s smooth and easy slide is one of its most highly appreciated features. There are also positive vertical serrations on the back of the slide that further enhance loading or unloading.The Sig Sauer P238 slide locks to the rear on an empty magazine, and the slide latch release is easy to reach with the thumb of the shooting hand. Similarly, the P238 has a user friendly manual thumb safety which further enhances shooter usability. The Sig Sauer P238 has stippling on the grips for a secure hold while firing the pistol. As mentioned, the frame has a generous beavertail to protect the web between the shooter’s thumb and trigger finger, and the hammer recesses into the beavertail section, to avoid any chance of hammer or slide-bite while firing the pistol. The Sig Sauer P238 is a very compact design, and while it may be slightly heavier than the polymer .380ACP pistols on the market, it is just as small.  We have 1 in stock, and have them priced to sell quickly for just $585 each.
